				\begin{document}$${\upphi }_{\mathrm{b}0}$$\end{document} is growing nonlinearly with the rising temperature. The nonlinearity serves as evidence that there is inhomogeneity in the barrier height at the interface [31]. We can also see that when the temperature rises, the ideality factor declines. There are a number of factors that contribute to this ideality factor, such as the uneven distribution of the interface state [32–35]. The low barrier zone can be crossed by carriers at low temperatures [30, 36–38]. Therefore, at low temperatures, the carriers will gather at the low barrier zones. As a result, in the low temperature area, we obtain a greater ideality factor and a lower barrier height. A nonlinear increase in the barrier height occurs as the temperature rises because at high temperatures more carriers are concentrated around the low barrier height regions and some thermally excited carriers are accumulated around the high barrier height domain.

Again we get the similar nature of the barrier height and ideality factor with the temperature in Fig. 7a and b for the dye incorporated with nanoparticles. But improvement of nonlinearity and slope of the nature or barrier height is the most prominent. This improvement can be addressed to the modification of inhomogeneity at the interface resulting a lower barrier height and greater conductivity. Figure 7c represents the schematic band diagram and the modification of barrier inhomogeneity by incorporated of nanoparticles. The room temperature barrier height and ideality factor for both the devices are given in the Table 2 below.Table 2
